## Answer

**Pi coding agent SDK for custom tools** — two registration paths, clear security model, pluggable operations for scope restriction.

---

## 1. How to Define Custom Tools

### via Extension (`pi.registerTool()`)

```typescript
import type { ExtensionAPI } from "@earendil-works/pi-coding-agent";
import { Type } from "typebox";

export default function (pi: ExtensionAPI) {
  pi.registerTool({
    name: "greet",
    label: "Greeting",
    description: "Greet someone by name",
    promptSnippet: "Greet a person",
    promptGuidelines: ["Use greet when the user asks to be greeted"],
    parameters: Type.Object({
      name: Type.String({ description: "Name to greet" }),
    }),
    async execute(toolCallId, params, signal, onUpdate, ctx) {
      return {
        content: [{ type: "text", text: `Hello, ${params.name}!` }],
        details: {},
      };
    },
  });
}
```

### via SDK (`defineTool()` + `customTools`)

```typescript
import { defineTool, createAgentSession } from "@earendil-works/pi-coding-agent";
import { Type } from "typebox";

const myTool = defineTool({
  name: "my_tool",
  label: "My Tool",
  description: "Does something useful",
  parameters: Type.Object({
    input: Type.String({ description: "Input value" }),
  }),
  execute: async (_toolCallId, params) => ({
    content: [{ type: "text", text: `Result: ${params.input}` }],
    details: {},
  }),
});

const { session } = await createAgentSession({
  customTools: [myTool],
  tools: ["read", "bash", "my_tool"],  // must include custom tool name
});
```

`defineTool()` preserves parameter type inference through arrays. Inline `pi.registerTool()` already infers correctly.

---

## 2. ToolDefinition Interface (Full Shape)

From `dist/core/extensions/types.d.ts`:

```typescript
export interface ToolDefinition<TParams extends TSchema, TDetails = unknown, TState = any> {
  name: string;
  label: string;
  description: string;
  promptSnippet?: string;                // One-line for "Available tools" in system prompt
  promptGuidelines?: string[];           // Bullets added to "Guidelines" section
  parameters: TParams;                   // TypeBox schema
  renderShell?: "default" | "self";      // Self-managed framing
  prepareArguments?: (args: unknown) => Static<TParams>; // Backward compat shim
  executionMode?: "sequential" | "parallel"; // Per-tool parallelism override
  execute(toolCallId: string, params: Static<TParams>, signal: AbortSignal | undefined,
          onUpdate: AgentToolUpdateCallback<TDetails> | undefined,
          ctx: ExtensionContext): Promise<AgentToolResult<TDetails>>;
  renderCall?: (args: Static<TParams>, theme: Theme, context: ToolRenderContext<TState, Static<TParams>>) => Component;
  renderResult?: (result: AgentToolResult<TDetails>, options: ToolRenderResultOptions,
                  theme: Theme, context: ToolRenderContext<TState, Static<TParams>>) => Component;
}
```

Key properties:
- **`name`** — used in system prompt tool definitions and LLM tool_call requests
- **`parameters`** — TypeBox schema; use `StringEnum` (from `@earendil-works/pi-ai`) instead of `Type.Union`/`Type.Literal` for Google API compatibility
- **`execute` return** — `{ content: TextContent[], details: TDetails, terminate?: boolean }`
- **`terminate: true`** — skips automatic follow-up LLM call (see `structured-output.ts` example)
- **Error signaling** — throw an Error to mark `isError: true`; returning never sets error flag
- **`promptSnippet`** — without it, custom tools are left out of the "Available tools" system prompt section

---

## 3. How Tools Are Registered with Subagents/Specialists

**Three registration paths:**

| Path | Method | Scope |
|------|--------|-------|
| Extension | `pi.registerTool()` | Global via `~/.pi/agent/extensions/` or project via `.pi/extensions/` |
| SDK | `createAgentSession({ customTools: [...] })` | Programmatic, embedded apps |
| SDK | `createAgentSession({ tools: ["name1", "name2"] })` | Enable/disable by name |

**Tool activation:** Tools must be both registered AND listed in the active tools set:

```typescript
// Extension manages active tools
pi.setActiveTools(["read", "bash", "my_tool"]);
pi.getActiveTools();    // string[]
pi.getAllTools();       // ToolInfo[] (name, description, parameters, promptGuidelines, sourceInfo)
```

**Dynamic registration at runtime** (see `dynamic-tools.ts`):
```typescript
pi.on("session_start", (_event, ctx) => {
  pi.registerTool({ ... });  // Register during startup or later
});
```

**Overriding built-in tools:** Register a tool with the same name as a built-in. Renderer inheritance is per-slot — omit `renderCall`/`renderResult` to keep the built-in's UI while overriding execution:

```typescript
pi.registerTool({
  name: "read",  // Same name → overrides built-in read
  // ...custom execute...
  // No renderCall/renderResult → built-in renderer used
});
```

**First registration wins** within extensions — the first extension to register a tool name gets it; later registrations with the same name are silently ignored.

---

## 4. Security Model & Restrictions

### Full system permissions for extensions
> **Security:** Extensions run with your full system permissions and can execute arbitrary code. Only install from sources you trust.

Extensions are TypeScript modules loaded via jiti. No sandbox by default.

### Tool call interception (gate pattern)
Extensions can block/modify ANY tool call via the `tool_call` event:

```typescript
pi.on("tool_call", async (event, ctx) => {
  if (event.toolName === "bash" && event.input.command?.includes("rm -rf")) {
    const ok = await ctx.ui.confirm("Dangerous!", "Allow rm -rf?");
    if (!ok) return { block: true, reason: "Blocked by user" };
  }
  // For write/edit tools
  if (event.toolName === "write" && event.input.path?.includes(".env")) {
    return { block: true, reason: "Protected path" };
  }
  return undefined; // Allow
});
```

### OS-level sandbox (sandbox example)
The `sandbox/` extension uses `@anthropic-ai/sandbox-runtime` to enforce filesystem and network restrictions at OS level (sandbox-exec on macOS, bubblewrap on Linux) via **overriding the bash tool's operations**:

```typescript
import { createBashTool, type BashOperations } from "@earendil-works/pi-coding-agent";

const sandboxedOps: BashOperations = {
  async exec(command, cwd, { onData, signal, timeout }) {
    const wrappedCommand = await SandboxManager.wrapWithSandbox(command);
    // spawn with sandbox wrapper...
  },
};

pi.registerTool({
  ...localBash,  // spread the built-in bash tool definition
  name: "bash",
  async execute(id, params, signal, onUpdate) {
    const sandboxedBash = createBashTool(cwd, { operations: sandboxedOps });
    return sandboxedBash.execute(id, params, signal, onUpdate);
  },
});
```

---

## 5. How to Restrict Tool Scope

### Pluggable Operations Interfaces

Built-in tools expose operations interfaces that let you swap the implementation without reimplementing the tool:

| Interface | Tool | Key Operations |
|-----------|------|---------------|
| `ReadOperations` | `read` | `readFile(path)`, `access(path)` |
| `WriteOperations` | `write` | `writeFile(path, content)` |
| `EditOperations` | `edit` | `editFile(path, edits)` |
| `BashOperations` | `bash` | `exec(command, cwd, options)` |
| `LsOperations` | `ls` | `readdir(path)` |
| `GrepOperations` | `grep` | `grep(pattern, path, glob)` |
| `FindOperations` | `find` | `find(pattern, path)` |

Example — restricting bash to a sandboxed filesystem:

```typescript
import { createBashTool, createLocalBashOperations } from "@earendil-works/pi-coding-agent";

const restrictedBash = createBashTool(cwd, {
  operations: createLocalBashOperations(),  // reuse local shell backend
  spawnHook: ({ command, cwd, env }) => ({
    command: `cd /sandbox && ${command}`,   // prefix with sandbox cd
    cwd: `/sandbox${cwd}`,
    env: { ...env, PATH: "/sandbox/usr/bin" },
  }),
});
```

### Spawn Hook (bash only)
Modify command, cwd, or env before execution:

```typescript
const bashTool = createBashTool(cwd, {
  spawnHook: ({ command, cwd, env }) => ({
    command: `source ~/.profile\n${command}`,
    cwd: `/mnt/sandbox${cwd}`,
    env: { ...env, CI: "1" },
  }),
});
```

### Selective tool enablement
```typescript
// Read-only agent: only non-destructive tools
pi.setActiveTools(["read", "grep", "find", "ls"]);

// Or via SDK
const { session } = await createAgentSession({
  tools: ["read", "grep", "find", "ls"],
});

// Disable ALL built-in tools, keep only extension tools
// pi --no-builtin-tools -e ./my-extension.ts
```

### Execution mode per tool
Prevent race conditions on shared state:

```typescript
pi.registerTool({
  name: "shared_state_tool",
  executionMode: "sequential",  // serializes with other tool calls
  // ...
});
```

### Output truncation (context safety)
All tools MUST truncate output to 50KB/2000 lines:

```typescript
import { truncateHead, truncateTail, DEFAULT_MAX_BYTES, DEFAULT_MAX_LINES } from "@earendil-works/pi-coding-agent";

const truncation = truncateHead(output, {
  maxLines: DEFAULT_MAX_LINES,
  maxBytes: DEFAULT_MAX_BYTES,
});
// Inform LLM if truncated + where full output saved
```

### State persistence for correct branching
Store tool state in `details` so branching works correctly:

```typescript
return {
  content: [{ type: "text", text: "Added todo" }],
  details: { action: "add", todos: [...todos], nextId },  // Full state snapshot
};
```

### Parallel tool execution queue
Tools that mutate files must use `withFileMutationQueue()` to participate in the per-file lock queue with built-in `edit`/`write`:

```typescript
import { withFileMutationQueue } from "@earendil-works/pi-coding-agent";

async execute(_toolCallId, params, _signal, _onUpdate, ctx) {
  const absolutePath = resolve(ctx.cwd, params.path);
  return withFileMutationQueue(absolutePath, async () => {
    // read-modify-write logic here — serialized per file
    const current = await readFile(absolutePath, "utf8");
    const next = current.replace(params.oldText, params.newText);
    await writeFile(absolutePath, next, "utf8");
    return { content: [{ type: "text", text: "Updated" }], details: {} };
  });
}
```

